{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474781"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:24:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:24:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12398"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12398"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.04,0.03,0.62,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4906"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53570"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4906"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12398"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39016"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1086"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7992"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8011"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15851"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53570"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother who is concerned about facial swelling that started to appear about two weeks ago. The swelling is generalised and is now also evident on his legs and abdomen. His mother reports that he is passing frothy urine and has gained around 4 kg in the last two weeks. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 110/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 13/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.6\u00b0C. His abdomen is distended with a positive fluid thrill. His lungs are clear to auscultation. There is pitting oedema on both ankles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["24-hour urine protein measurement","Renal biopsy","CT of kidneys, ureters and bladder","Spot urine protein/creatinine ratio","Renal ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical scenario of generalised oedema, weight gain, and the presence of frothy urine is highly suggestive of nephrotic syndrome. Nephrotic syndrome is characterised by massive proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, hyperlipidaemia, and oedema. It is caused by increased permeability through the damaged basement membrane in the renal glomeruli.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate initial investigation in this case is a \u003Cstrong\u003Espot urine protein/creatinine ratio\u003C/strong\u003E. This test is easy to obtain, has nearly equal accuracy to a 24-hour urine test, and provides an average measurement of protein produced over 24 hours. It helps in evaluating proteinuria and thus reaching the diagnosis quickly and efficiently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urine protein\u003C/strong\u003E measurement is also used for the diagnosis of nephrotic syndrome. However, a spot urine protein/creatinine ratio is preferred as the initial test because it is faster, cheaper, and gives a relatively quick evaluation of protein loss. A 24-hour urine protein measurement can then be carried out after the initial demonstration of proteinuria if needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough a \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard diagnostic test for nephrotic syndrome and other renal pathologies, it is invasive and has potential complications. Therefore, it would not be used as the initial investigation. It may be considered later in the diagnostic process, especially if the cause of nephrotic syndrome is unclear or if it\u0027s necessary to guide treatment decisions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT of kidneys, ureters and bladder\u003C/strong\u003E would not be an appropriate initial investigation in this case. While it can help evaluate the anatomy of the urinary system, it has no role in determining the functional disorder which has led to the signs and symptoms in this patient. Additionally, it involves radiation exposure, which should be avoided if not necessary, especially in paediatric patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not the correct option in this scenario. While imaging studies can be useful in evaluating the underlying cause of nephrotic syndrome or identifying complications, they are not the initial diagnostic investigation. Ultrasound might be considered later in the workup to assess kidney size and echogenicity, or to rule out complications such as renal vein thrombosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter confirming proteinuria with the spot urine protein/creatinine ratio, further investigations would typically include serum albumin, lipid profile, and renal function tests. Management would focus on treating the underlying cause (if identified), managing oedema with diuretics, and potentially using immunosuppressive therapy depending on the specific type of nephrotic syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spot urine protein/creatinine ratio is the best initial test for nephrotic syndrome.","Nephrotic syndrome is characterised by massive proteinuria, hypoalbuminemia, hyperlipidaemia, and oedema.","Renal biopsy is the gold standard for diagnosis of nephrotic syndrome but is not the initial investigation due to its invasive nature."],"references":["Tapia C, Bashir K. Nephrotic Syndrome. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470444/","Tamura H. Trends in pediatric nephrotic syndrome. World J Nephrol. 2021 Sep 25;10(5):88-100. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8477269/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39016"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12398"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39016"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-22T20:08:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-22T20:08:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4906"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53570"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":